Sure, here are the core SVG bits stripped down:

1. Create the SVG canvas
js

const SVG_NS = 'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg';
const CENTER = { x: 200, y: 200 };

const svg = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'svg');
svg.setAttribute('viewBox', '0 0 400 400');

const defs = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'defs');
const arrowsGroup = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'g');
svg.append(defs, arrowsGroup);

// Center dot
const dot = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'circle');
dot.setAttribute('cx', CENTER.x);
dot.setAttribute('cy', CENTER.y);
dot.setAttribute('r', 6);
dot.setAttribute('fill', '#2a3f3d');
svg.appendChild(dot);

Key thing: SVG elements need createElementNS with the SVG namespace, not createElement.

2. Compute arrow endpoints from magnitude + angle
js

const SCALE = 2.5;  // pixels per Newton
const len = mag * SCALE;
const rad = -angle * Math.PI / 180;  // negate because SVG y-axis is flipped
const tipX = CENTER.x + len * Math.cos(rad);
const tipY = CENTER.y + len * Math.sin(rad);

The -angle is the trick — in math 90° is up, but in SVG y increases downward. Negating the angle makes 90° point up like students expect.

3. Draw the arrow line
js

const line = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'line');
line.setAttribute('x1', CENTER.x);
line.setAttribute('y1', CENTER.y);
line.setAttribute('x2', tipX);
line.setAttribute('y2', tipY);
line.setAttribute('stroke', color);
line.setAttribute('stroke-width', 3);
line.setAttribute('marker-end', `url(#${markerId})`);
arrowsGroup.appendChild(line);

4. Add an arrowhead (marker)

Markers are reusable arrowheads defined once in <defs>, then attached to lines via marker-end:
js

const marker = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'marker');
marker.setAttribute('id', markerId);
marker.setAttribute('viewBox', '0 0 10 10');
marker.setAttribute('refX', 8);  // where the line "meets" the marker
marker.setAttribute('refY', 5);
marker.setAttribute('markerWidth', 5);
marker.setAttribute('markerHeight', 5);
marker.setAttribute('orient', 'auto');  // rotates with the line direction

const path = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'path');
path.setAttribute('d', 'M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z');  // triangle
path.setAttribute('fill', color);
marker.appendChild(path);
defs.appendChild(marker);

You need a separate marker per color, hence the unique markerId per force.

5. Position label perpendicular to the arrow
js

const perpRad = rad - Math.PI / 2;  // 90° offset from arrow direction
const labelX = tipX + 16 * Math.cos(perpRad);
const labelY = tipY + 16 * Math.sin(perpRad);

const text = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'text');
text.setAttribute('x', labelX);
text.setAttribute('y', labelY);
text.setAttribute('text-anchor', 'middle');
text.setAttribute('dominant-baseline', 'middle');
text.setAttribute('fill', color);
text.textContent = `${name} (${mag}N)`;
arrowsGroup.appendChild(text);

text-anchor and dominant-baseline center the text on the (x,y) point — without them, labels anchor weirdly at the bottom-left.

6. Re-render on state change

The simplest pattern: clear and rebuild the whole arrows group every time something changes.
js

function renderDiagram() {
    arrowsGroup.innerHTML = '';
    defs.innerHTML = '';
    forces.forEach((f, i) => {
        // ... create marker, line, text and append
    });
}

This is fast enough for any FBD that fits on screen (well under 100 elements). No need for diffing.

That's the whole pattern: compute endpoints from polar (magnitude, angle) → create line + marker + text → append to a group → wipe and rebuild on changes. Everything else is layout and styling.